<TITLE>Detroit Regional Transportation Authority makes early, $13.5 million debt payment that will save taxpayers</TITLE>


<TEXT>
12:01 a.m.  Updated 
 Operating losses for <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DATE" value="X">the seventh</TIMEX3> consecutive year to near-break-even   
EMBARGOED UNTIL <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DATE" value="2017-01-29">SUNDAY</TIMEX3>, 1/29 AT NOON 
 
The Detroit Regional Convention Facility Authority <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE">narrowed</EVENT> its operational <EVENT eid="e2" class="OCCURRENCE">loss</EVENT> for <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="DATE" value="2016">the seventh consecutive year in 2016</TIMEX3> after <EVENT eid="e3" class="OCCURRENCE">paying</EVENT> down $13.5 million in taxable bonds, a move it <EVENT eid="e4" class="REPORTING">says</EVENT> will <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE">save</EVENT> taxpayers about $11.7 million over the life of the bond issue or $7.75 million in <TIMEX3 tid="t4" type="DATE" value="X">present</TIMEX3> value dollars. 
 
The early payment <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE">represented</EVENT> more than half of the higher-interest $23.5 million taxable bond issue <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">owed</EVENT> on the original $295.35 million in bonds taken out in <TIMEX3 tid="t5" type="DATE" value="2014-11">November 2014</TIMEX3>, <EVENT eid="e8" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT> Patrick Bero, CEO and COO of the authority, which <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE">has</EVENT> operational oversight for Detroits Cobo Center. 
 
It was <EVENT eid="e10" class="OCCURRENCE">made</EVENT> in addition to a scheduled principal payment of just over $7 million <EVENT eid="e11" class="OCCURRENCE">paid</EVENT> <TIMEX3 tid="t6" type="DATE" value="2016-10">last October</TIMEX3>. 
 
<TIMEX3 tid="t7" type="DATE" value="2018">Next year</TIMEX3>, the authority <EVENT eid="e12" class="I_STATE">plans</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e13" class="OCCURRENCE">pay</EVENT> off the remainder of the taxable bond issue and then <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE">dip</EVENT> into the tax-exempt debt <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE">owed</EVENT>, Bero <EVENT eid="e16" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT>. 
 
The early payment <EVENT eid="e17" class="OCCURRENCE">leaves</EVENT> the authority owing a total of just under $274.8 million, Bero <EVENT eid="e18" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT>, due at various points between <TIMEX3 tid="t8" type="DATE" value="PRESENT_REF">now</TIMEX3> and <TIMEX3 tid="t9" type="DATE" value="2039">2039</TIMEX3>. 
 
The authority <EVENT eid="e19" class="OCCURRENCE">continued</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e20" class="OCCURRENCE">operate</EVENT> at a <EVENT eid="e21" class="OCCURRENCE">loss</EVENT> <TIMEX3 tid="t10" type="DATE" value="2016">last year</TIMEX3> but <EVENT eid="e22" class="OCCURRENCE">narrowed</EVENT> its deficit to $280,166 earnings before interest, depreciation and amortization, net of debt and operating subsidies. 
 
The authority and Cobo management company SNG have <EVENT eid="e23" class="OCCURRENCE">narrowed</EVENT> the <EVENT eid="e24" class="OCCURRENCE">losses</EVENT> for seven consecutive years since <EVENT eid="e25" class="OCCURRENCE">taking</EVENT> on oversight of the convention center. 
 
In <TIMEX3 tid="t11" type="DATE" value="2015">2015</TIMEX3> it <EVENT eid="e26" class="OCCURRENCE">posted</EVENT> a $2.7 million <EVENT eid="e27" class="OCCURRENCE">loss</EVENT> and $3.4 million loss the <TIMEX3 tid="t12" type="DURATION" value="PXY">year</TIMEX3> before. 
 
The city was <EVENT eid="e28" class="OCCURRENCE">losing</EVENT> an estimated $21 million year on Cobo Center, the authority <EVENT eid="e29" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT>, when it <EVENT eid="e30" class="OCCURRENCE">took</EVENT> over control in <TIMEX3 tid="t13" type="DATE" value="2009-09">September 2009</TIMEX3> under an <EVENT eid="e31" class="OCCURRENCE">agreement</EVENT> between the Michigan State Legislature, the City of Detroit, and Wayne, Oakland and Macomb counties. 
 
Bero <EVENT eid="e32" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT> the authority is <EVENT eid="e33" class="OCCURRENCE">approaching</EVENT> a break-even point operationally, <TIMEX3 tid="t14" type="DURATION" value="P7Y">nearly seven years</TIMEX3> before the <TIMEX3 tid="t15" type="DATE" value="2023">2023</TIMEX3> deadline the state legislature <EVENT eid="e34" class="OCCURRENCE">set</EVENT> as <TIMEX3 tid="t16" type="DATE" value="2016">the last year</TIMEX3> it will <EVENT eid="e35" class="OCCURRENCE">receive</EVENT> subsidies to <EVENT eid="e36" class="OCCURRENCE">help</EVENT> fund Cobos operation. He <EVENT eid="e37" class="STATE">credits</EVENT> the recent renovation and subsequent <EVENT eid="e38" class="OCCURRENCE">increase</EVENT> in bookings with <EVENT eid="e39" class="I_ACTION">helping</EVENT> the events venue turn things around. 
 
The authority <EVENT eid="e40" class="OCCURRENCE">completed</EVENT> a $279 million <EVENT eid="e41" class="OCCURRENCE">renovation</EVENT> and upgrade to Cobo Center on time and within budget in <TIMEX3 tid="t17" type="DATE" value="2015-08">August 2015</TIMEX3>. Among other things, the upgrades <EVENT eid="e42" class="OCCURRENCE">created</EVENT> a 30,000-square-foot atrium with views of the Detroit River and Canada, <EVENT eid="e43" class="OCCURRENCE">increased</EVENT> parking and <EVENT eid="e44" class="OCCURRENCE">improved</EVENT> traffic flow, upgraded infrastructure, enclosed loading <EVENT eid="e45" class="OCCURRENCE">docks</EVENT> and <EVENT eid="e46" class="OCCURRENCE">redeveloped</EVENT> the former Cobo Arena as a 40,000-square-foot grand ballroom. 
 
Additionally, the authority <EVENT eid="e47" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT> a $2 million technology upgrade was <EVENT eid="e48" class="ASPECTUAL">completed</EVENT> in mid-December to <EVENT eid="e49" class="OCCURRENCE">allow</EVENT> 32,000 simultaneous users on Cobos Wi-Fi network. 
 
In <TIMEX3 tid="t18" type="DATE" value="2016">2016</TIMEX3>, the event center <EVENT eid="e50" class="OCCURRENCE">hosted</EVENT> 16 city-wide conventions, including the annual North American International Auto Show. 
 
Cobo <EVENT eid="e51" class="OCCURRENCE">lays</EVENT> claim to being the 17th largest convention center in the country with 723,000 square feet of exhibition space and nearly 1.5 million visitors each year.
</TEXT>


